result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 08:41 AM Defendant, Allen Ray Butler, appeared with Attorney James McLaughlin.  Attorney Jospeh Schieffer  appeared for the State. Atty McLaughlin files PLQ and recites agreement, Pleading 112, 63, 288 all other DRI 2 fe BJ, and 1 count of  Burglery, 3 yrs probation, withheld, 9 month county jail. 34 days jail credit. report to jail w/in 60 days from today. No contact w/victims $2,170.52 restitution. Request for domestic huber and/or elec monitor. The State addresses the Court for reasoning to this agreement. will be requesting a rest. hrg. Sentencing will be scheduled for another day. The Court examines Def. it is his signature on the PLQ and per Atty McLaughlin he has thouroughly gone over the Plq with the Def., he can read, write and understands the english language. He understands the constitutional rights he is waiving today. The State has enough evidence to prove his guilt beyond a reasonable doubt. He admits to the facts of burglery, he admits to commiting a new crime, and he admits to commiting a 2nd new crime, Atty McLaughlin states he stole from Dreamers Bar. He understands the citizenship law. The Court is not bound by this agreement, he could be sentenced to the max. He has had enough time to discuss these matters w/his Attorney. He understands the DRI charges. No threats or promises made for him to plead today. in 16CF112 Def. enters G plea, in 17CF22 Def. enters G Plea, and in the last case enters G plea to another FE BJ. Stip to factual basis for Pleas     The Court finds him G of these. The Court orders PSI. Bond to continue  Sentencing hearing scheduled for March 13, 2019 at 03:30 pm.
